                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">856D.6176/373: Telegram (part air)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-12T12:00:00+00:19"
                            >December 12, 1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 14—6:55
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>68. Department’s telegram 38, December 5, 4 p.m.<note n="10" xml:id="d425fn10"
                        >See footnote 7, <ref target="#pg_513">p. 513</ref>.</note> Colonel
                    Townsend, Mr. Newman and Viles saw Van Gelderen, chief Netherlands Delegate in
                    the International Rubber Committee yesterday afternoon. He gave them
                    satisfactory assurances. The Dutch think more or less as we do but are not
                    prepared to vote for a reduction of restriction to 20 per cent unless they are
                    convinced that there are no technical obstacles and that that much rubber can be
                    delivered.</p>
                <p>I did some informal groundwork before their arrival but Colonel Townsend thinks
                    that written or oral representations in the sense of the Department’s
                    instruction unnecessary at the moment. I agree. There is no resentment at all
                    here such as appears to exist in London but will nevertheless take no further
                    steps unless instructed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
